<dl id="n12056f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12056f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12056f"> 56(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Norman Leslie / Kirkcaldy of Grange <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>nge<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> / Pitmillie</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Aucun doute n&apos;est plus possible sur l&apos;identit&eacute; des &eacute;cossais enferm&eacute;s au Mont et que ne nomme pas de Bourgueville. Nirmont Lessetay n&apos;est autre que Norman Lesley, Millort de Grange, Kirkcaldy of Grange et le seigneur du Petimel, Pitmillie. Cette alt&eacute;ration dans l&apos;orthographe des noms est tr&egrave;s fr&eacute;quente, quand il s&apos;agit de transcrire des noms propres &eacute;trangers. / Ces d&eacute;tenus &eacute;taient des personnes d&eacute;marque. / Norman Lesley fut, on le sait, un des champions les plus distingu&eacute;s de la R&eacute;forme en Ecosse. En 1546, Lesley, &agrave; la t&ecirc;te d&apos;une petite troupe de quinze hommes, &eacute;gorgea le cardinal Beaton au ch&acirc;teau de Saint-Andr&eacute; et s&apos;enferma dans la place qu&apos;il venait de prendre avec Knox, le grand r&eacute;formateur de l&apos;&eacute;cosse. <br><font color="green">[No doubt is possible on the identity of the Scotsman imprisoned on the Mont and whose name is not given by Bourgueville. Nirmont Lessetay is no other than <mark>Norman Lesley</mark>, Millort de Grange, <mark>Kirkcaldy of Grange</mark> and the lord of Petimel, <mark>Pitmillie</mark>. The orthographic shift of the names its frequent when it involves the transcription of foreign names. These prisoners were men of renown. Norman Lesley was, we know, one of the most distinguished champions of the Scottish Reformation. In 1546 Lesley, at the head of a small group of fifteen men, butchered cardinal Beaton at the castle of Saint Andrew and locked himself in the fortress he had just taken with <mark>Knox</mark>, the great Scottish reformer.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 155</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Norman Leslie, master of Rothes, and William Kirkcaldy of Grange were involved in the murder of Cardinal Beaton at St Andrews on 29 May 1546. Knoxite (usu. Knoxian): follower of John Knox (c. 1505-1572), Scottish reformer; he founded the Scottish Presbterian Church. </mm> </dd></dl>
